<paper id="1893432122"><title>Globus and PlanetLab resource management solutions compared</title><year>2004</year><authors><author org="Chicago University, USA" id="1576812999">M. Ripeanu</author><author org="Intel Research#TAB#" id="2974615357">M. Bowman</author><author org="â€¢ Duke University#TAB#" id="2147241376">J.S. Chase</author><author org="The University of Chicago and Argonne National Lab" id="2017222965">I. Foster</author><author org="Intel Research#TAB#" id="2974601549">M. Milenkovic</author></authors><n_citation>21</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1517860926</reference><reference>1942766326</reference><reference>1968526517</reference><reference>1969490101</reference><reference>1978004294</reference><reference>1997802075</reference><reference>2002546113</reference><reference>2008206224</reference><reference>2018301820</reference><reference>2054278783</reference><reference>2062728787</reference><reference>2066191928</reference><reference>2071958655</reference><reference>2081461624</reference><reference>2084445812</reference><reference>2091257550</reference><reference>2096199913</reference><reference>2097116331</reference><reference>2098981715</reference><reference>2100129018</reference><reference>2104210894</reference><reference>2111996486</reference><reference>2113959882</reference><reference>2115806861</reference><reference>2116258061</reference><reference>2117588623</reference><reference>2118428193</reference><reference>2118436132</reference><reference>2123732385</reference><reference>2126831426</reference><reference>2133884536</reference><reference>2136784730</reference><reference>2141438662</reference><reference>2144553078</reference><reference>2150676586</reference><reference>2152526229</reference><reference>2153752068</reference><reference>2154010459</reference><reference>2155444313</reference><reference>2156644501</reference><reference>2157689518</reference><reference>2158049821</reference><reference>2162232794</reference><reference>2163059190</reference><reference>2163185337</reference><reference>2167898414</reference><reference>2439240014</reference></references><venue id="1141854641" type="C">High Performance Distributed Computing</venue><doi>10.1109/HPDC.2004.17</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.48646">Network service</keyword><keyword weight="0.53579">Resource management</keyword><keyword weight="0.45199">World Wide Web</keyword><keyword weight="0.6246">PlanetLab</keyword><keyword weight="0.51044">Grid computing</keyword><keyword weight="0.4364">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.47648">Testbed</keyword><keyword weight="0.51649">Resource allocation</keyword><keyword weight="0.51542">Shared resource</keyword><keyword weight="0.44682">Distributed computing</keyword><keyword weight="0.48262">Project management</keyword></keywords><publisher>IEEE</publisher><abstract>PlanetLab and Globus Toolkit are gaining widespread adoption in their respective communities. Although designed to solve different problems - PlanetLab is deploying a worldwide infrastructure testbed for experimenting with network services, while Globus is offering general, standards-based, software for running distributed applications over aggregated, shared resources - both build infrastructures that enable federated, extensible, and secure resource sharing across trust domains. Thus, it is instructive to compare their resource management solutions. To this end, we review the approaches taken in the two systems, attempt to trace back to starting assumptions the differences in these approaches, and explore scenarios where the two platforms can cooperate to the benefit of both user communities. We believe that this is a key first step to identifying pieces that could be shared by the two communities, pieces that are complementary, and how Globus and PlanetLab might ultimately evolve together.</abstract></paper>